[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] AFL Ontario, along with the North West Pacific Football League is a member of AFL Canada, the governing body for the sport in Canada.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] AFL Ontario which was originally known as the Canadian Australian Football League (CAFA) and more recently as the Ontario Australian Football League (OAFL), was established in 1989.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] Two teams were formed that year - the Toronto Panthers and the Mississauga Mustangs, with a draft of interested players prior to a three-game season and Grand Final.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] The coaches of those inaugural teams – John Pearson (Toronto Panthers) and Terence Wallis (Mississauga Mustangs) brought a significant amount of experience from playing at a high level in Australia.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] An interesting fact is that the first Grand Final was attended by a number of AFL executives including Ron Barrassi and members of the Geelong Cats and Melbourne Demons.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] These pioneers set the foundation for the current competition.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] During the early years CAFA played a number of International games against visiting teams from Australia (Balmain FC, Golden Oldies touring team) as well as the team representing the Australian Rules league in England.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] The Canadian team narrowly missed beating the touring Australian teams over the years, but soundly defeated England on the four occasions that it played them (1990–1996) culminating in a strong win by the touring Canadian team in London (1996) coached by Terence Wallis.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] In 2011, with the increased interest in women's football, AFL Ontario established their Women's League with great success.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] With the help of the Ontario Trillium Foundation, 2011 also saw the development of AFL Ontario's junior competition.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] 2012 saw the women's division double in size to 6 teams competing, and the junior competition continued over the summer holidays.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] In 2009, AFL Ontario launched a second division originally consisting of six founding teams.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] London (Ontario) AFC withdrew before the official start to the season and the team's players were absorbed into the Quebec Saints.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] Along with the Saints, the Toronto Central Blues, Broadview Hawks, Etobicoke 'Old Boys' Roos and Toronto Eagles made up the founding five teams of the new OAFL Division 2 competition.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] In honour of the first Canadian to ever play in the AFL the competition's premiership cup was named the **Mike Pyke Cup** (named after Mike Pyke).
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] The OAFL Division 2 season was traditionally shorter than that of the OAFL.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] In 2009 due to teams playing different numbers of matches the ladder was determined by 'Match Ratio' rather than premiership points.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] In 2010 all teams competed in 8 rounds and thus the ladder reverted to determining positions by premiership points.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] 2010 also saw the introduction of hybrid teams.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] New team the Toronto Rebel Dogs (a partnership between the Toronto Downtown Dingos and the Toronto Rebels) and the 'DevilRoos' (a partnership between the Etobicoke Roos and High Park Demons).
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] The Toronto Eagles withdrew their team from the 2010 season.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] Location map of current clubs in the league.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] In 2006, AFL Ontario had around 330 senior players consisting of over 170 Canadian nationals.
[src:afl-canada/afl-ontario] With the rapid increase in awareness and interest in Australian football in Ontario, this has increased in 2012 with almost 650 senior men and women members.
